# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: temperature-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] A **bimetallic strip** or **bimetal strip** is a strip that consists of two strips of different metals which expand at different rates as they are heated.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The different expansion rates cause the strip to bend one way if heated, and in the opposite direction if cooled below its initial temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Thus, a bimetal strip converts a temperature change into mechanical displacement.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The metal with the higher coefficient of thermal expansion is on the outer side of the curve when the strip is heated and on the inner side when cooled.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Common applications include temperature sensing (thermometer) and regulation (thermostat).
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The invention of the bimetallic strip is generally credited to John Harrison, an eighteenth-century clockmaker who made it for his third marine chronometer (H3) of 1759 to compensate for temperature-induced changes in the balance spring.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Harrison's invention is recognized in the memorial to him in Westminster Abbey, England.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The strip consists of two strips of different metals which expand at different rates as they are heated, usually steel and copper, or in some cases steel and brass.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The strips are joined throughout their length by riveting, brazing or welding.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The different expansions force the flat strip to bend one way if heated, and in the opposite direction if cooled below its initial temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The sideways displacement of the strip is much larger than the small lengthways expansion in either of the two metals.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] In some applications, the bimetal strip is used in the flat form.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] In others, it is wrapped into a coil for compactness.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The greater length of the coiled version gives improved sensitivity.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] For each metallic strip: $E_{i}$ is the Young modulus, $\alpha _{i}$ is the coefficient of thermal expansion and $h_{i}$ is the thickness.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The formula can also be rewritten as a function of the thermal misfit strain $\Delta \epsilon =(\alpha _{2}-\alpha _{1})(T-T_{0})$ .
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] And if the modulus and height are similar, we simply have $a\simeq 1$ .
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] An equivalent formula can be derived from the beam theory.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The earliest surviving bimetallic strip was made by the eighteenth-century clockmaker John Harrison who is generally credited with its invention.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] He made it for his third marine chronometer (H3) of 1759 to compensate for temperature-induced changes in the balance spring.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] It should not be confused with the bimetallic mechanism for correcting for thermal expansion in his gridiron pendulum.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] His earliest examples had two individual metal strips joined by rivets but he also invented the later technique of directly fusing molten brass onto a steel substrate.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] A strip of this type was fitted to his last timekeeper, H5.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The metals involved in a bimetallic strip can vary in composition so long as their coefficients of thermal expansion differ significantly.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The metal with the lower thermal expansion coefficient is called the passive (or low-expansion) metal, while the other is called the active (or high-expansion) metal.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Material selection has a significant impact on the operating temperature range and sensitivity of the bimetallic strip.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Some combinations can operate up to 500 °C, while others are limited to approximately 150 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Bimetallic strips are typically manufactured by bonding two different metals together.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] After bonding, the strip is often annealed (heat-treated) to relieve internal stresses and then rolled or drawn to the desired thickness.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Precise control of the thickness ratio between the two layers is critical, as it directly affects the sensitivity and curvature of the final strip.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Modern manufacturing processes allow for very thin bimetallic strips (down to 0.1 mm or less) and long coils, enabling their use in compact devices such as miniature circuit breakers and precision thermostats.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Bimetallic strips are used in many temperature-sensing and control devices due to their ability to convert temperature changes into mechanical movement.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Mechanical clock mechanisms are sensitive to temperature changes as each part has tiny tolerance and it leads to errors in time keeping.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] A bimetallic strip is used to compensate this phenomenon in the mechanism of some timepieces.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The most common method is to use a bimetallic construction for the circular rim of the balance wheel.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] What it does is move a weight in a radial way looking at the circular plane down by the balance wheel, varying then, the momentum of inertia of the balance wheel.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] As the spring controlling the balance becomes weaker with the increasing temperature, the balance becomes smaller in diameter to decrease the momentum of inertia and keep the period of oscillation (and hence timekeeping) constant.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Nowadays this system is not used anymore since the appearance of low temperature coefficient alloys like nivarox, parachrom and many others depending on each brand.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] In the regulation of heating and cooling, thermostats that operate over a wide range of temperatures are used.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] In these, one end of the bimetallic strip is mechanically fixed and attached to an electrical power source, while the other (moving) end carries an electrical contact.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] In adjustable thermostats another contact is positioned with a regulating knob or lever.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The position so set controls the regulated temperature, called the *set point*.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Some thermostats use a mercury switch connected to both electrical leads.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The angle of the entire mechanism is adjustable to control the set point of the thermostat.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Depending upon the application, a higher temperature may open a contact (as in a heater control) or it may close a contact (as in a refrigerator or air conditioner).
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The electrical contacts may control the power directly (as in a household iron) or indirectly, switching electrical power through a relay or the supply of natural gas or fuel oil through an electrically operated valve.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] In some natural gas heaters the power may be provided with a thermocouple that is heated by a pilot light (a small, continuously burning, flame).
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] A direct indicating dial thermometer, common in household devices (such as a patio thermometer or a meat thermometer), uses a bimetallic strip wrapped into a coil in its most common design.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] The coil changes the linear movement of the metal expansion into a circular movement thanks to the helicoidal shape it draws.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] One end of the coil is fixed to the housing of the device as a fix point and the other drives an indicating needle inside a circular indicator.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] A bimetallic strip is also used in a recording thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Breguet's thermometer consists of a tri-metallic helix in order to have a more accurate result.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Heat engines are not the most efficient ones, and with the use of bimetallic strips the efficiency of the heat engine is even lower as there is no chamber to contain the heat.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Moreover, the bimetallic strips cannot produce strength in its moves, the reason why is that in order to achieve reasonables bendings (movements) both metallic strips have to be thin to make the difference between the expansion noticeable.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] So the uses for metallic strips in heat engines are mostly in simple toys that have been built to demonstrate how the principle can be used to drive a heat engine.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] When the temperature of an area has risen, the metals of the bimetallic strip which are bonded together in the fire alarm each expand at a different rate upon heating.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] When the strip is heated, the metal with the higher coefficient of Thermal expansion bends towards the metal with the lower coefficient.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] This bending action is used to close a circuit, which triggers the alarm or any other function used in the alarm.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Bimetal strips are used in miniature circuit breakers to protect circuits from excess current.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] A coil of wire is used to heat a bimetal strip, which bends and operates a linkage that unlatches a spring-operated contact.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] This interrupts the circuit and can be reset when the bimetal strip has cooled down.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] Bimetal strips are also used in time-delay relays, gas oven safety valves, thermal flashers for older turn signal lamps, and fluorescent lamp starters.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] In some devices, the current running directly through the bimetal strip is sufficient to heat it and operate contacts directly.
[src:temperature-sensors/bimetallic-strip] It has also been used in mechanical PWM voltage regulators for automotive uses.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] An **infrared thermometer** is a thermometer which infers temperature from a portion of the thermal radiation, sometimes called black-body radiation, emitted by the object being measured.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] They are sometimes called **laser thermometers** as a laser is used to help aim the thermometer, or **non-contact thermometers** or **temperature guns**, to describe the device's ability to measure temperature from a distance.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] By knowing the amount of infrared energy emitted by the object and its emissivity, the object's temperature can often be determined within a certain range of its actual temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Infrared thermometers are a subset of devices known as "thermal radiation thermometers".
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Sometimes, especially near ambient temperatures, readings may be subject to error due to the reflection of radiation from a hotter body, or due to an incorrectly assumed emissivity.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] The design essentially consists of a lens to focus the infrared thermal radiation on to a detector, which converts the radiant power to an electrical signal that can be displayed in units of temperature after being compensated for ambient temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] This permits temperature measurement from a distance without contact with the object to be measured.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] A non-contact infrared thermometer is useful for measuring temperature under circumstances where thermocouples or other probe-type sensors cannot be used or do not produce accurate data for a variety of reasons.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Infrared thermometers can be used to serve a wide variety of temperature monitoring functions.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] At times of epidemics of diseases causing fever, such as SARS coronavirus and Ebola virus disease, infrared thermometers have been used to check arriving travelers for fever without causing harmful transmissions among the tested.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] In 2020 when COVID-19 pandemic hit the world, infrared thermometers were used to measure people's temperature and deny them entry to potential transmission sites if they showed signs of fever.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Public health authorities such as the FDA in United States published rules to assure accuracy and consistency among the infrared thermometers.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] There are many varieties of infrared temperature-sensing devices, both for portable and handheld use and as fixed installations.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Infrared thermometers are characterized by specifications including accuracy and angular coverage.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Simpler instruments may have a measurement error of about ± 2 °C (3.6 °F).
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] The distance-to-spot ratio (D:S) is the ratio of the distance to the measurement surface and the diameter of the temperature measurement area.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] For instance, if the D:S ratio is 12:1, the diameter of the measurement area is one-twelfth of the distance to the object.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] A thermometer with a higher ratio of D to S is able to sense a more-specific, narrower surface at a greater distance than one with a lower ratio.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] A 12:1 rated device can sense a 1-inch circle at a distance of one foot, whereas a 10:1 ratio device achieves the same 1-inch circle at 10 inches, and a wider, less-specific circle of 1.2 inches at a distance of 12 inches.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] The ideal target area should be at least twice the size of the spot at that distance, with smaller areas relative to distance resulting in less accurate measurement.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] An infrared thermometer should not be placed too close to a hot target, as this proximity could cause heat to build up in the thermometer's housing and damage the sensor.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Measurement error generally only decreases with too much distance because of the effects of reflectivity and the inclusion of other heat sources within the sensor's field of view.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] According to the Stefan–Boltzmann law, radiant power is proportional to the fourth power of temperature, so when the measurement surface has both hot and cold areas, the indicated temperature may be higher than the actual average temperature, and closer to fourth-power mean average.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Most surfaces have high emissivity (over 0.9 for most biological surfaces), and most IR thermometers rely on this simplifying assumption; however, reflective surfaces have lower emissivity than non-reflective surfaces.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Some sensors have an adjustable emissivity setting, which can be set to measure the temperature of reflective and non-reflective surfaces.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] A non-adjustable thermometer may be used to measure the temperature of a reflective surface by applying a non-reflective paint or tape, with some loss of accuracy.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] A sensor with an adjustable emissivity setting can also be used to calibrate the sensor for a given surface or to measure the emissivity of a surface.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] The most common infrared thermometer is the spot infrared pyrometer or infrared pyrometer, which measures the temperature at a spot on a surface (actually a relatively small area determined by the D:S ratio).
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] These usually project a visible red dot onto the center of the area being measured that identifies the spot being measured, but plays no part in the measurement.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] The actual angular area being measured varies among instruments and is not restricted to the visible spot.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Related equipment, although not strictly thermometers, include infrared scanning systems and infrared thermal imaging cameras.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Infrared scanning systems scan a larger area, typically by using what is essentially a spot thermometer pointed at a rotating mirror.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] These devices are widely used in manufacturing involving conveyors or "web" processes, such as large sheets of glass or metal exiting an oven, fabric, and paper, or continuous piles of material along a conveyor belt.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Infrared thermal imaging cameras or infrared cameras are essentially infrared radiation thermometers that measure the temperature at many points over a relatively large area to generate a two-dimensional image, called a thermogram, with each pixel representing a temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] This technology is more processor- and software-intensive than spot or scanning thermometers, and is used for monitoring large areas.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] Typical applications include perimeter monitoring used by military or security personnel, inspection/process quality monitoring of manufacturing processes, and equipment or enclosed space hot or cold spot monitoring for safety and efficiency maintenance purposes.
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] A photographic camera using infrared film and suitable lens, etc., is also called an "infrared camera".
[src:temperature-sensors/infrared-thermometer] This only captures the near-infrared and is not sensitive to the thermal radiation from room-temperature objects.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Attempts at standardized temperature measurement prior to the 17th century were crude at best.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] For instance in 170 AD, physician Claudius Galenus mixed equal portions of ice and boiling water to create a "neutral" temperature standard.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The modern scientific field has its origins in the works by Florentine scientists in the 1600s including Galileo constructing devices able to measure relative change in temperature, but subject also to confounding with atmospheric pressure changes.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] These early devices were called thermoscopes.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The first sealed thermometer was constructed in 1654 by the Grand Duke of Tuscany, Ferdinand II.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The development of today's thermometers and temperature scales began in the early 18th century, when Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit produced a mercury thermometer and scale, both developed by Ole Christensen Rømer.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Fahrenheit's scale is still in use, alongside the Celsius and Kelvin scales.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Many methods have been developed for measuring temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Most of these rely on measuring some physical property of a working material that varies with temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] One of the most common devices for measuring temperature is the mercury-in-glass thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] This consists of a glass tube filled with mercury or some other liquid, which acts as the working fluid.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Temperature increase causes the fluid to expand, so the temperature can be determined by measuring the volume of the fluid.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Such thermometers are usually calibrated so that one can read the temperature simply by observing the level of the fluid in the thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Another type of thermometer that is not really used much in practice, but is important from a theoretical standpoint, is the gas thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] One must be careful when measuring temperature to ensure that the measuring instrument (thermometer, thermocouple, etc.) is really the same temperature as the material that is being measured.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Under some conditions heat from the measuring instrument can cause a temperature gradient, so the measured temperature is different from the actual temperature of the system.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] In such a case the measured temperature will vary not only with the temperature of the system, but also with the heat transfer properties of the system.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] What thermal comfort humans, animals and plants experience is related to more than temperature shown on a glass thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Relative humidity levels in ambient air can induce more or less evaporative cooling.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Measurement of the wet-bulb temperature normalizes this humidity effect.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Mean radiant temperature also can affect thermal comfort.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The wind chill factor makes the weather feel colder under windy conditions than calm conditions even though a glass thermometer shows the same temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Airflow increases the rate of heat transfer from or to the body, resulting in a larger change in body temperature for the same ambient temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The theoretical basis for thermometers is the zeroth law of thermodynamics which postulates that if you have three bodies, A, B and C, if A and B are at the same temperature, and B and C are at the same temperature then A and C are at the same temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The practical basis of thermometry is the existence of triple point cells.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Triple points are conditions of pressure, volume and temperature such that three phases are simultaneously present, for example solid, vapor and liquid.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] For a single component there are no degrees of freedom at a triple point and any change in the three variables results in one or more of the phases vanishing from the cell.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Therefore, triple point cells can be used as universal references for temperature and pressure (see Gibbs phase rule).
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Under some conditions it becomes possible to measure temperature by a direct use of the Planck's law of black-body radiation.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] For example, the cosmic microwave background temperature has been measured from the spectrum of photons observed by satellite observations such as the WMAP.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] In the study of the quark–gluon plasma through heavy-ion collisions, single-particle spectra sometimes serve as a thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] During recent decades, many thermometric techniques have been developed.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The most promising and widespread non-invasive thermometric techniques in a biotech context are based on the analysis of magnetic resonance images, computerized tomography images and echotomography.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] These techniques allow monitoring temperature within tissues without introducing a sensing element.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] In the field of reactive flows (e.g., combustion, plasmas), laser induced fluorescence (LIF), CARS, and laser absorption spectroscopy have been exploited to measure temperature inside engines, gas-turbines, shock-tubes, synthesis reactors etc.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The capability of such optical-based techniques include rapid measurement (down to nanosecond timescales), notwithstanding the ability to *not* perturb the subject of measurement (e.g., the flame, shock-heated gases).
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Atmospheric temperature is a measure of temperature at different levels of the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] It is governed by many factors, including incoming solar radiation, humidity, and altitude.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The abbreviation MAAT is often used for Mean Annual Air Temperature of a geographical location.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] The American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) has developed two separate and distinct standards on temperature Measurement, B40.200 and PTC 19.3.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] B40.200 provides guidelines for bimetallic-actuated, filled-system, and liquid-in-glass thermometers.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] It also provides guidelines for thermowells.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] PTC 19.3 provides guidelines for temperature measurement related to Performance Test Codes with particular emphasis on basic sources of measurement errors and techniques for coping with them.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Atmospheric temperature trends from 1979-2016 based on satellite measurements; troposphere above, stratosphere below.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Satellite temperature measurements are inferences of the temperature of the atmosphere at various altitudes as well as sea and land surface temperatures obtained from radiometric measurements by satellites.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] These measurements can be used to locate weather fronts, monitor the El Niño-Southern Oscillation, determine the strength of tropical cyclones, study urban heat islands and monitor the global climate.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Wildfires, volcanos, and industrial hot spots can also be found via thermal imaging from weather satellites.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Weather satellites do not measure temperature directly.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] They measure radiances in various wavelength bands.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Since 1978 microwave sounding units (MSUs) on National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration polar orbiting satellites have measured the intensity of upwelling microwave radiation from atmospheric oxygen, which is related to the temperature of broad vertical layers of the atmosphere.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Measurements of infrared radiation pertaining to sea surface temperature have been collected since 1967.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Satellite datasets show that over the past four decades the troposphere has warmed and the stratosphere has cooled.
[src:temperature-sensors/temperature-measurement] Both of these trends are consistent with the influence of increasing atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] A **thermistor** is a semiconductor type of resistor in which the resistance is strongly dependent on temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The word *thermistor* is a portmanteau of *thermal* and *resistor*.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The varying resistance with temperature allows these devices to be used as temperature sensors, or to control current as a function of temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Some thermistors have decreasing resistance with temperature, while other types have increasing resistance with temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This allows them to be used for limiting current to cold circuits, e.g. for inrush current protection, or for limiting current to hot circuits, e.g. to prevent thermal runaway.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Thermistors are categorized based on their conduction models.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] *Negative-temperature-coefficient* (NTC) thermistors have *less* resistance at *higher* temperatures, while *positive-temperature-coefficient* (PTC) thermistors have *more* resistance at *higher* temperatures.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] NTC thermistors are widely used as inrush current limiters and temperature sensors, while PTC thermistors are used as self-resetting overcurrent protectors and self-regulating heating elements.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The operational temperature range of a thermistor is dependent on the material and is typically between −100 and 300 °C (−148 and 572 °F).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Thermistors are generally produced using powdered metal oxides.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] With formulas and techniques vastly improving over the past 20 years as of 2020, NTC thermistors can now achieve accuracies over wide temperature ranges such as ±0.1 °C or ±0.2 °C from 0 °C to 70 °C with excellent long-term stability.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] NTC thermistor elements come in many styles, such as axial-leaded glass-encapsulated (DO-35, DO-34 and DO-41 diodes), glass-coated chips, epoxy-coated with bare or insulated lead wire and surface-mount, as well as thin film versions.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The typical operating temperature range of a thermistor is −55 °C to +150 °C, though some glass-body thermistors have a maximal operating temperature of +300 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Thermistors differ from resistance temperature detectors (RTDs) in that the material used in a thermistor is generally a ceramic or polymer, while RTDs use pure metals.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The temperature response is also different; RTDs are useful over larger temperature ranges, while thermistors typically achieve a greater precision within a limited temperature range, typically −90 °C to 130 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Depending on type of the thermistor in question the k may be either positive or negative.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] If k is positive, the resistance increases with increasing temperature, and the device is called a *positive-temperature-coefficient* (*PTC*) *thermistor*, or *posistor*.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] There are two types of PTC resistor – *switching thermistor* and *silistor*.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] If k is negative, the resistance decreases with increasing temperature, and the device is called a *negative-temperature-coefficient* (*NTC*) *thermistor*.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Resistors that are not thermistors are designed to have a k as close to 0 as possible so that their resistance remains nearly constant over a wide temperature range.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Instead of the temperature coefficient *k*, sometimes the *temperature coefficient of resistance* $\alpha _{T}$ ("alpha sub T") is used.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This $\alpha _{T}$ coefficient should not be confused with the a parameter below.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Thermistors are typically built by using metal oxides.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] They're typically pressed into a bead, disk, or cylindrical shape and then encapsulated with an impermeable material such as epoxy or glass.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] NTC thermistors are manufactured from oxides of the iron group of metals: e.g. chromium (CrO, Cr2O3), manganese (e.g.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] MnO), cobalt (CoO), iron (iron oxides), and nickel (NiO, Ni2O3). these oxides form a ceramic body with terminals composed of conductive metals such as silver, nickel, and tin.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] PTC thermistors are usually prepared from barium (Ba), strontium, or lead titanates (e.g.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Thermistors can also be produced by resonant acoustic mixing of the previously mentioned oxides, followed by a sintering process.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This effort reduces production time and can eliminate the calcination step entirely.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] In practical devices, the linear approximation model (above) is accurate only over a limited temperature range.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Over wider temperature ranges, a more complex resistance–temperature transfer function provides a more faithful characterization of the performance.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] where *a*, *b* and *c* are called the Steinhart–Hart parameters and must be specified for each device.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] *T* is the absolute temperature, and *R* is the resistance.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The equation is not dimensionally correct, since a change in the units of R results in an equation with a different form, containing a $(\ln R)^{2}$ term.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] In practice, the equation gives good numerical results for resistances expressed in, for example, ohms (Ω) or kiloohms, but the coefficients a, b, and c must be stated with reference to that particular unit.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The error in the Steinhart–Hart equation is generally less than 0.02 °C in the measurement of temperature over a 200 °C range.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] where the temperatures and the *B* parameter are in kelvins, and *R*0 is the resistance of the thermistor at temperature *T*0 (25 °C = 298.15 K).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The *B*-parameter equation can also be written as $\ln R=B/T+\ln r_{\infty }$ .
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This can be used to convert the function of resistance vs. temperature of a thermistor into a linear function of $\ln R$ vs. $1/T$ .
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The average slope of this function will then yield an estimate of the value of the *B* parameter.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Many NTC thermistors are made from a pressed disc, rod, plate, bead or cast chip of semiconducting material such as sintered metal oxides.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] They work because raising the temperature of a semiconductor increases the number of active charge carriers by promoting them into the *conduction band*.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The more charge carriers that are available, the more current a material can conduct.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] In certain materials like ferric oxide (Fe2O3) with titanium (Ti) doping an *n-type* semiconductor is formed and the charge carriers are electrons.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] In materials such as nickel oxide (NiO) with lithium (Li) doping a *p-type* semiconductor is created, where holes are the charge carriers.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Over large changes in temperature, calibration is necessary.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Over small changes in temperature, if the right semiconductor is used, the resistance of the material is linearly proportional to the temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] There are many different semiconducting thermistors with a range from about 0.01 kelvin to 2,000 kelvins (−273.14 °C to 1,700 °C).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The IEC standard symbol for a NTC thermistor includes a "−t°" under the rectangle.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Most PTC thermistors are made from doped polycrystalline ceramic (containing barium titanate (BaTiO3) and other compounds) which have the property that their resistance rises suddenly at a certain critical temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Barium titanate is ferroelectric and its dielectric constant varies with temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Below the Curie point temperature, the high dielectric constant prevents the formation of potential barriers between the crystal grains, leading to a low resistance.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] In this region the device has a small negative temperature coefficient.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] At the Curie point temperature, the dielectric constant drops sufficiently to allow the formation of potential barriers at the grain boundaries, and the resistance increases sharply with temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] At even higher temperatures, the material reverts to NTC behaviour.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Another type of thermistor is a **silistor** (a thermally sensitive silicon resistor).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Silistors employ silicon as the semiconductive component material.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Unlike ceramic PTC thermistors, silistors have an almost linear resistance-temperature characteristic.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Silicon PTC thermistors have a much smaller drift than an NTC thermistor.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] They are stable devices which are hermetically sealed in an axial leaded glass encapsulated package.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Barium titanate thermistors can be used as self-controlled heaters; for a given voltage, the ceramic will heat to a certain temperature, but the power used will depend on the heat loss from the ceramic.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The dynamics of PTC thermistors being powered lends to a wide range of applications.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] When first connected to a voltage source, a large current corresponding to the low, cold, resistance flows, but as the thermistor self-heats, the current is reduced until a limiting current (and corresponding peak device temperature) is reached.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The current-limiting effect can replace fuses.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] In the degaussing circuits of many CRT monitors and televisions an appropriately chosen thermistor is connected in series with the degaussing coil.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This results in a smooth current decrease for an improved degaussing effect.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Some of these degaussing circuits have auxiliary heating elements to heat the thermistor (and reduce the resulting current) further.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Another type of PTC thermistor is the polymer PTC, which is sold under brand names such as "Polyswitch" "Semifuse", and "Multifuse".
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This consists of plastic with carbon grains embedded in it.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] When the plastic is cool, the carbon grains are all in contact with each other, forming a conductive path through the device.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] When the plastic heats up, it expands, forcing the carbon grains apart, and causing the resistance of the device to rise, which then causes increased heating and rapid resistance increase.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Like the BaTiO3 thermistor, this device has a highly nonlinear resistance/temperature response useful for thermal or circuit control, not for temperature measurement.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Besides circuit elements used to limit current, self-limiting heaters can be made in the form of wires or strips, useful for heat tracing.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] PTC thermistors "latch" into a hot / high resistance state: once hot, they stay in that high resistance state, until cooled.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The effect can be used as a primitive latch/memory circuit, the effect being enhanced by using two PTC thermistors in series, with one thermistor cool, and the other thermistor hot.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The IEC standard symbol for a PTC thermistor includes a "+t°" under the rectangle.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] When a current flows through a thermistor, it generates heat, which raises the temperature of the thermistor above that of its environment.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] If the thermistor is being used to measure the temperature of the environment, this electrical heating may introduce a significant error (an observer effect) if a correction is not made.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Alternatively, this effect itself can be exploited.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] It can, for example, make a sensitive air-flow device employed in a sailplane rate-of-climb instrument, the electronic variometer, or serve as a timer for a relay as was formerly done in telephone exchanges.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] where *I* is current, and *V* is the voltage drop across the thermistor.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This power is converted to heat, and this heat energy is transferred to the surrounding environment.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] where *T*(*R*) is the temperature of the thermistor as a function of its resistance *R*, $T_{0}$ is the temperature of the surroundings, and *K* is the *dissipation constant*, usually expressed in units of milliwatts per degree Celsius.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The current and voltage across the thermistor depend on the particular circuit configuration.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The dissipation constant is a measure of the thermal connection of the thermistor to its surroundings.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] It is generally given for the thermistor in still air and in well-stirred oil.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Typical values for a small glass-bead thermistor are 1.5 mW/°C in still air and 6.0 mW/°C in stirred oil.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] If the temperature of the environment is known beforehand, then a thermistor may be used to measure the value of the dissipation constant.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] For example, the thermistor may be used as a flow-rate sensor, since the dissipation constant increases with the rate of flow of a fluid past the thermistor.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The power dissipated in a thermistor is typically maintained at a very low level to ensure insignificant temperature measurement error due to self-heating.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] However, some thermistor applications depend upon significant "self-heating" to raise the body temperature of the thermistor well above the ambient temperature, so the sensor then detects even subtle changes in the thermal conductivity of the environment.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Some of these applications include liquid-level detection, liquid-flow measurement and air-flow measurement.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] The first NTC thermistor was discovered in 1833 by Michael Faraday, who reported on the semiconducting behavior of silver sulfide.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Faraday noticed that the resistance of silver sulfide decreased dramatically as temperature increased.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] This was also the first documented observation of a semiconducting material.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] Because early thermistors were difficult to produce and applications for the technology were limited, commercial production of thermistors did not begin until the 1930s.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermistor] A commercially viable thermistor was invented by Samuel Ruben in 1930.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] A **thermometer** is a device that measures temperature (the hotness or coldness of an object) or temperature gradient (the rates of change of temperature in space).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers are widely used in technology and industry to monitor processes, in meteorology, in medicine (*medical thermometer*), and in scientific research.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] While an individual thermometer is able to measure degrees of hotness, the readings on two thermometers cannot be compared unless they conform to an agreed scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Today there is an absolute thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Internationally agreed temperature scales are designed to approximate this closely, based on fixed points and interpolating thermometers.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The most recent official temperature scale is the International Temperature Scale of 1990.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Sparse and conflicting historical records make it difficult to pinpoint the invention of the thermometer to any single person or date with certitude.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In addition, given the many parallel developments in the thermometer's history and its many gradual improvements over time, the instrument is best viewed not as a single invention, but an evolving technology.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Early pneumatic devices and ideas from antiquity provided inspiration for the thermometer's invention during the Renaissance period.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In the 3rd century BC, Philo of Byzantium documented his experiment with a tube submerged in a container of liquid on one end and connected to an air-tight, hollow sphere on the other.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] When air in the sphere is heated with a candle or by exposing it to the sun, expanding air exits the sphere and generates bubbles in the vessel.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] As air in the sphere cools, a partial vacuum is created, sucking liquid up into the tube.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Any changes in the position of the liquid will now indicate whether the air in the sphere is getting hotter or colder.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Translations of Philo's experiment from the original ancient Greek were utilized by Robert Fludd sometime around 1617 and used as the basis for his air thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In his book, *Pneumatics*, Hero of Alexandria (10–70 AD) provides a recipe for building a "Fountain which trickles by the Action of the Sun's Rays," a more elaborate version of Philo's pneumatic experiment but which worked on the same principle of heating and cooling air to move water around.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Translations of the ancient work *Pneumatics* were introduced to late 16th century Italy and studied by many, including Galileo Galilei, who had read it by 1594.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The Roman Greek physician Galen is given credit for introducing two concepts important to the development of a scale of temperature and the eventual invention of the thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] First, he had the idea that hotness or coldness may be measured by "degrees of hot and cold." He also conceived of a fixed reference temperature, a mixture of equal amounts of ice and boiling water, with four degrees of heat above this point and four degrees of cold below.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] 16th century physician Johann Hasler developed body temperature scales based on Galen's theory of degrees to help him mix the appropriate amount of medicine for patients.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In the late 16th and early 17th centuries, several European scientists, notably Galileo Galilei and Italian physiologist Santorio Santorio, developed devices with an air-filled glass bulb, connected to a tube, partially filled with water.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] As the air in the bulb warms or cools, the height of the column of water in the tube falls or rises, allowing an observer to compare the current height of the water to previous heights to detect relative changes of the heat in the bulb and its immediate environment.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Such devices, with no scale for assigning a numerical value to the height of the liquid, are referred to as a *thermoscope* because they provide an observable indication of sensible heat (the modern concept of temperature was yet to arise).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The difference between a thermoscope and a thermometer is that the latter has a scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Given this, Middleton claimed that the possible inventors of the thermometer are Galileo, Santorio, Dutch inventor Cornelis Drebbel, or British mathematician Robert Fludd.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Though Galileo is often said to be the inventor of the thermometer, there is no surviving document that he actually produced any such instrument.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The first clear diagram of a thermoscope was published in 1617 by Giuseppe Biancani (1566 – 1624); the first showing a scale and thus constituting a thermometer was by Santorio Santorio in 1625.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] This was a vertical tube, closed by a bulb of air at the top, with the lower end opening into a vessel of water.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The water level in the tube was controlled by the expansion and contraction of the air, so it was what we would now call an air thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The word thermometer (in its French form) first appeared in 1624 in *La Récréation Mathématique* by Jean Leurechon, who describes one with a scale of 8 degrees.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The word comes from Ancient Greek θερμός (*thermós*), meaning "warmth", and μέτρον (*métron*), meaning "measure".
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The above instruments suffered from the disadvantage that they were also barometers, i.e. sensitive to air pressure.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In 1629, Joseph Solomon Delmedigo, a student of Galileo and Santorio in Padua, published what is apparently the first description and illustration of a sealed liquid-in-glass thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] It is described as having a bulb at the bottom of a sealed tube partially filled with brandy.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Delmedigo did not claim to have invented this instrument.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Nor did he name anyone else as its inventor.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In about 1654, Ferdinando II de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany (1610–1670) did produce such an instrument, the first modern-style thermometer, dependent on the expansion of a liquid and independent of air pressure.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Many other scientists experimented with various liquids and designs of thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] However, each inventor and each thermometer was unique — there was no standard scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Early attempts at standardization added a single reference point such as the freezing point of water.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In 1701, Isaac Newton (1642–1726/27) proposed a scale of 12 degrees between the melting point of ice and body temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In 1714, scientist and inventor Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit invented a reliable thermometer, using mercury instead of alcohol and water mixtures.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In 1724, he proposed a temperature scale which now (slightly adjusted) bears his name.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In 1742, Anders Celsius (1701–1744) proposed a scale with zero at the boiling point and 100 degrees at the freezing point of water, though the scale which now bears his name has them the other way around.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] French entomologist René Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur invented an alcohol thermometer and, temperature scale in 1730, that ultimately proved to be less reliable than Fahrenheit's mercury thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The first physician to use thermometer measurements in clinical practice was Herman Boerhaave (1668–1738).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In 1866, Sir Thomas Clifford Allbutt (1836–1925) invented a clinical thermometer that produced a body temperature reading in five minutes as opposed to twenty.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Traditional thermometers were all non-registering thermometers.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] That is, the thermometer did not hold the temperature reading after it was moved to a place with a different temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Determining the temperature of a pot of hot liquid required the user to leave the thermometer in the hot liquid until after reading it.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] If the non-registering thermometer was removed from the hot liquid, then the temperature indicated on the thermometer would immediately begin changing to reflect the temperature of its new conditions (in this case, the air temperature).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Registering thermometers are designed to hold the temperature indefinitely, so that the thermometer can be removed and read at a later time or in a more convenient place.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Mechanical registering thermometers are designed to hold the highest or lowest temperature reached until they are manually reset, such as by shaking down a mercury-in-glass thermometer, or until an even more extreme temperature occurs.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Electronic registering thermometers can be programmed either to store the highest or lowest temperature reached, or to record the temperature at a specific point in time.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers increasingly use electronic means to provide a digital display or input to a computer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers may be described as empirical or absolute.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Absolute thermometers are calibrated numerically by the thermodynamic absolute temperature scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] For any two empirical thermometers, this does not require that the relation between their numerical scale readings be linear, but it does require that relation to be strictly monotonic.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] This is a fundamental character of temperature and thermometers.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] There are several principles on which empirical thermometers are built, as listed in the section of this article entitled "Primary and secondary thermometers".
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Several such principles are essentially based on the constitutive relation between the state of a suitably selected particular material and its temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Only some materials are suitable for this purpose, and they may be considered as "thermometric materials".
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Radiometric thermometry, in contrast, can be only slightly dependent on the constitutive relations of materials.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In a sense then, radiometric thermometry might be thought of as "universal".
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] This is because it rests mainly on a universality character of thermodynamic equilibrium, that it has the universal property of producing blackbody radiation.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] There are various kinds of empirical thermometer based on material properties.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Many empirical thermometers rely on the constitutive relation between pressure, volume and temperature of their thermometric material.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] For example, mercury expands when heated.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] (1) Its heating and cooling must be rapid.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Some materials do not have this property, and take some time to distribute the heat between temperature and volume change.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] (2) Its heating and cooling must be reversible.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] That is to say, the material must be able to be heated and cooled indefinitely often by the same increment and decrement of heat, and still return to its original pressure, volume and temperature every time.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] (3) Its heating and cooling must be monotonic.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] but not (i) for some temperatures and (ii) for others.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] At temperatures around about 4 °C, water does not have the property (3), and is said to behave anomalously in this respect; thus water cannot be used as a material for this kind of thermometry for temperature ranges near 4 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Consequently, they are suitable thermometric materials, and that is why they were important in the development of thermometry.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] According to Preston (1894/1904), Regnault found constant pressure air thermometers unsatisfactory, because they needed troublesome corrections.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] He therefore built a constant volume air thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Constant volume thermometers do not provide a way to avoid the problem of anomalous behaviour like that of water at approximately 4 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] A small enough hole in the wall of the cavity emits near enough blackbody radiation of which the spectral radiance can be precisely measured.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The walls of the cavity, provided they are completely opaque and poorly reflective, can be of any material indifferently.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] A thermometer is called primary or secondary based on how the raw physical quantity it measures is mapped to a temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] As summarized by Kauppinen et al., "For **primary thermometers** the measured property of matter is known so well that temperature can be calculated without any unknown quantities.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In contrast, "Secondary thermometers are most widely used because of their convenience.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Also, they are often much more sensitive than primary ones.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] For secondary thermometers knowledge of the measured property is not sufficient to allow direct calculation of temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] They have to be calibrated against a primary thermometer at least at one temperature or at a number of fixed temperatures.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers can be calibrated either by comparing them with other calibrated thermometers or by checking them against known fixed points on the temperature scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The best known of these fixed points are the melting and boiling points of pure water.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Immerse the sensing portion in a steam bath at standard atmospheric pressure and again mark the point indicated.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Divide the distance between these marks into equal portions according to the temperature scale being used.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] (This is an example of a frigorific mixture.) As body temperature varies, the Fahrenheit scale was later changed to use an upper fixed point of boiling water at 212 °F (100 °C).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] These have now been replaced by the defining points in the International Temperature Scale of 1990, though in practice the melting point of water is more commonly used than its triple point, the latter being more difficult to manage and thus restricted to critical standard measurement.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Nowadays manufacturers will often use a thermostat bath or solid block where the temperature is held constant relative to a calibrated thermometer.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Other thermometers to be calibrated are put into the same bath or block and allowed to come to equilibrium, then the scale marked, or any deviation from the instrument scale recorded.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] For many modern devices calibration will be stating some value to be used in processing an electronic signal to convert it to a temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The *precision* or *resolution* of a thermometer is simply to what fraction of a degree it is possible to make a reading.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] For high temperature work it may only be possible to measure to the nearest 10 °C or more.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Clinical thermometers and many electronic thermometers are usually readable to 0.1 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Special instruments can give readings to one thousandth of a degree.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] However, this precision does not mean the reading is true or accurate, it only means that very small changes can be observed.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] A thermometer calibrated to a known fixed point is accurate (i.e. gives a true reading) at that point.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] The invention of the technology to measure temperature led to the creation of scales of temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In between fixed calibration points, interpolation is used, usually linear.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] This may give significant differences between different types of thermometer at points far away from the fixed points.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] For example, the expansion of mercury in a glass thermometer is slightly different from the change in resistance of a platinum resistance thermometer, so these two will disagree slightly at around 50 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] There may be other causes due to imperfections in the instrument, e.g. in a liquid-in-glass thermometer if the capillary tube varies in diameter.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] For many purposes reproducibility is important.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] That is, does the same thermometer give the same reading for the same temperature (or do replacement or multiple thermometers give the same reading)?
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Reproducible temperature measurement means that comparisons are valid in scientific experiments and industrial processes are consistent.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thus if the same type of thermometer is calibrated in the same way its readings will be valid even if it is slightly inaccurate compared to the absolute scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] According to British Standards, correctly calibrated, used and maintained liquid-in-glass thermometers can achieve a measurement uncertainty of ±0.01 °C in the range 0 to 100 °C, and a larger uncertainty outside this range: ±0.05 °C up to 200 or down to −40 °C, ±0.2 °C up to 450 or down to −80 °C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] BET systems require a specialized optical system, as well as custom data analysis software.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] for which the spectra is directly proportional to the temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] It has the advantage of remote temperature sensing; it does not require contact or even close proximity unlike most thermometers.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] are useful over a wide temperature range from cryogenic temperatures to over 1000°C, but typically have an error of ±0.5-1.5°C.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] ) but in fact exhibit a temperature dependence.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] of a paramagnetic material exhibits an inverse temperature dependence.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers utilize a range of physical effects to measure temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Temperature sensors are used in a wide variety of scientific and engineering applications, especially measurement systems.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Temperature systems are primarily either electrical or mechanical, occasionally inseparable from the system which they control (as in the case of a mercury-in-glass thermometer).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers are used in roadways in cold weather climates to help determine if icing conditions exist.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Indoors, thermistors are used in climate control systems such as air conditioners, freezers, heaters, refrigerators, and water heaters.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Galileo thermometers are used to measure indoor air temperature, due to their limited measurement range.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Such liquid crystal thermometers (which use thermochromic liquid crystals) are also used in mood rings and used to measure the temperature of water in fish tanks.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Fiber Bragg grating temperature sensors are used in nuclear power facilities to monitor reactor core temperatures and avoid the possibility of nuclear meltdowns.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Nanothermometry is an emergent research field dealing with the knowledge of temperature in the sub-micrometric scale.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Conventional thermometers cannot measure the temperature of an object which is smaller than a micrometre, and new methods and materials have to be used.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Nanothermometers are classified as luminescent thermometers (if they use light to measure temperature) and non-luminescent thermometers (systems where thermometric properties are not directly related to luminescence).
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers used specifically for low temperatures.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Various thermometric techniques have been used throughout history such as the Galileo thermometer to thermal imaging.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Medical thermometers such as mercury-in-glass thermometers, infrared thermometers, pill thermometers, and liquid crystal thermometers are used in health care settings to determine if individuals have a fever or are hypothermic.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers are important in food safety, where food at temperatures within 41 and 135 °F (5 and 57 °C) can be prone to potentially harmful levels of bacterial growth after several hours which could lead to foodborne illness.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] This includes monitoring refrigeration temperatures and maintaining temperatures in foods being served under heat lamps or hot water baths.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Cooking thermometers are important for determining if a food is properly cooked.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] In particular meat thermometers are used to aid in cooking meat to a safe internal temperature while preventing over cooking.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] They are commonly found using either a bimetallic coil, or a thermocouple or thermistor with a digital readout.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Candy thermometers are used to aid in achieving a specific water content in a sugar solution based on its boiling temperature.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Alcohol thermometers, infrared thermometers, mercury-in-glass thermometers, recording thermometers, thermistors, and Six's thermometers (maximum-minimum thermometer) are used in meteorology and climatology in various levels of the atmosphere and oceans.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Aircraft use thermometers and hygrometers to determine if atmospheric icing conditions exist along their flight path.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] These measurements are used to initialize weather forecast models.
[src:temperature-sensors/thermometer] Thermometers are used in roadways in cold weather climates to help determine if icing conditions exist and indoors in climate control systems.
